We saw this flag hanging in a window of the temporary city office of Minamisanriku while gathering information for an upcoming story (the original office was swept away by the tsunami).  It was sent by residents of Aomori prefecture to show their support for the people of Minamisanriku.  The large letters above the rising sun read, "Gambarou," which translates as "Do your best" or "Hang in there." Jim Seida
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: This is the view from our hotel in Minamisanriku.  It's a resort hotel that mostly survived the tsunami - they have food, but no running water in the rooms.  On March 11, the tsunami rolled across Shizugawa Bay, seen here, on its way to wiping out Minamisanriku.  Jim Seida
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Seen from the car while driving in Minamisanriku.  Kyle says it's a play on words in Japanese.  Anybody know what it means? Jim Seida, msnbc.com

status_message: Nahoko, left, Miranda and Kyle discuss whether we should turn around and find a different route south because of the stuck truck. status_message: The people at the Yu restaurant where we are say it's the first loss of power since the immediate tsunami aftermath  #afterthewave
We're about to have dinner in the dark due to a power outage. The owner invited us in and we're hungry!  #afterthewave

I met the daughter of the Chiba family whom we profiled. I hadn't met her before. Earlier last week, they moved out of the shelter into a home. I asked what she thought about it and she said, "It's nice to be home." Five simple words with such big meaning. I wish them all the best. Here is the story if you missed it http://on.msnbc.com/l2Wvil If you're curious, I saw her at the jazz ensemble, more to come on that!

status_message: Today, we met a kids' jazz ensemble. We'll tell you their story soon, but for now I thought I'd share this clip. Their leader told Jim Seida, msnbc.com that his first name means "administrator" in Japanese and jokingly asked if he worked in administration. At one point, he asked me, "Miranda-san" where does Route 66 begin and end? And with that, enjoy this from the Swing Dolphins.

We're en route to Miyako on the coast. I've asked the people from Miyako Update to come over here and tell us about what the city is like, the people, the jobs they do and how the tsunami has impacted them. We're going to stay at a shelter -- not using any of their resources, bringing our own stuff -- so let us know what you'd like us to find out! Miranda Leitsinger msnbc.com

status_message: Reflecting on this from Mr. Haga, who wants to move his tsunami-hit town up the hill to a new future. I think these ring true for many people in different ways: "Most of the people around here are either farmers or fishermen .. Being in those industries means that you have to help people and accept help from others. ... That's part of being in a community. Everything revolves around the fact that we help each other."

Here is Jim Seida, msnbc.com in action on Tuesday for the green story that wants to rebuild their community in a new place together. Just thought we'd show you a little bit of the backstory. Check back later for the story! Miranda Leitsinger msnbc.com
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Jim Seida, msnbc.com takes us on a drive to the Japanese coastal town of Kesennuma, where an idyllic countryside gives way to miles of tsunami destruction. - Josh Belzman at msnbc.com
link_name: In Japan, a drive toward destruction

status_message: Here's the report on the couple that Miranda and Jim encountered on their way to another assignment. Sweet story! - Mike Brunker, msnbc.com
link_name: World Blog - After tsunami, elderly couple rebuilds a 'small life'

status_message: We were heading south on our way to Koizumi, south of Kesennuma, to report on a small town that's considering rebuilding their community higher up in the hills when Kyle, our driver, spotted an enormous area littered with destroyed vehicles and homes off to our right.  "We're nowhere near the water," he said.  Our Toyota Estima's GPS confirmed that we were more than a kilometer from the coast - the ocean was nowhere in sight.  Jim Seida, msnbc.com
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: We are about to head out the door on a 2-drive to a small town destroyed by the tsunami where half the people want to rebuild their community -- and they want to rebuild it green! What kinds of tips would you have for them? What do you think are the key elements of building a 'green' community? We'll tell you more about their effort - stay tuned! Miranda Leitsinger msnbc.com
The latest World Blog post from Jim and Miranda, on how a father-son team of electricians in Kesennuma found the courage to carry on. - Mike Brunker, msnbc.com
link_name: World Blog - For father-son electricians, 'ganbaru' provided a spark

status_message: Cars are stacked atop one another in Saichi, outside Kesennuma, Japan Monday, June 6, 2011.  #Jim Seida, msnbc.com
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: I'm working on a story about a family rebuilding their business in the devastated fishing port of Kesennuma in northern Japan. They all kept using the Japanese term "Ganbaru!" in our interviews. Do you know what it means, how people use the term? Write it here. I found it inspiring. Oh! And what do you think is the equivalent in English? Miranda Leitsinger msnbc.com
You should have seen the clock, stopped at 2:46 - the time of the quake. Apart from the devastation right in front of us, it spoke volumes. Miranda Leitsinger msnbc.com
link_name: World Blog - A moment's devastation, a long road to recovery

status_message: These boats piled up along the shore of the Kitakami River, just northeast of Ishinomaki City, are the first signs we've seen of the tsunami.  (Jim Seida / msnbc.com)
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: After I got off a Skype call in our minivan, I looked over and saw a guy waterskiing in a river in Chiba! Pretty cool.  #afterthewave
Just had a good chat with Sarajean Rossitto of Give2Asia about some issues up north: helping the elderly, the disabled.  #afterthewave

We tried multiple ATMs in Nariat to get some cash before heading north - according to Lonely Planet, Japan is very much a cash society.  I struck out at every one I tried.  Miranda was able to withdraw 20,000 Yen ($248 US) before the machine rejected her card.  It's Sunday here, banks are closed.  Heading north - Miranda and Jim #afterthewave
and Rikuzentakata, where the coast's contours helped the waves rush inland. We'll go as far as we can, until dark!  #afterthewave
... the devastated fishing port of Kesennuma, along the Kitakami river -- which the tsunami surged 50 meters up ...  #afterthewave
Hi everyone, so we've mapped a route along the coast that will take us past the rice farming area of Toyoma ...  #afterthewave
